To generate an automatic table of contents in a LaTeX document, you can use the following commands:

1. Include the `book` or `report` class and the `tocloft` package in your preamble:
   ```latex
\documentclass{book}
\usepackage{tocloft}
```
   The `book` class provides a good structure for generating a table of contents, while the `tocloft` package offers additional features for customizing the TOC.

2. Define the structure of your document by using sections, subsections, and other heading commands. For example:
   ```latex
\chapter{Introduction}
\section{Background}
\subsection{Motivation}
\chapter{Methodology}
```
   LaTeX will automatically detect these headings and use them to generate the table of contents.

3. Use the `\tableofcontents` command to generate the table of contents:
   ```latex
\tableofcontents
```
   This command will create a table of contents based on the headings defined in your document.

4. Use the `\setlength` and `\renewcommand` commands to customize the table of contents:
   ```latex
\setlength{\cftchapterindent}{2em}
\renewcommand{\cftchapfont}{\sffamily\bfseries}
```
   The first command sets the indentation for chapter headings, while the second command changes the font for chapter headings to sans-serif bold.

Here's a complete example:

```latex
\documentclass{book}
\usepackage{tocloft}

\setlength{\cftchapterindent}{2em}
\renewcommand{\cftchapfont}{\sffamily\bfseries}

\begin{document}

\chapter{Introduction}
\section{Background}
\subsection{Motivation}
\chapter{Methodology}

\tableofcontents

\chapter{Introduction}
This is the introduction.

\section{Background}
This is the background.

\subsection{Motivation}
This is the motivation.

\chapter{Methodology}
This is the methodology.

\end{document}
```
